   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Merry
                           Wives of Windsor</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Merry Wives of Windsor</title>; A Comedy, In
                              Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                                 Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. III. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>As You
                              Like It</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Merry Wives of
                              Windsor</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryVIIIKingofEngland">King Henry
                              VIII</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Measure for
                              Measure</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Winter's
                              Tale</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at
                        Windsor Castle on April 23<hi rendition="#sup">rd</hi>, 1597. Laura DeWitt
                        and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The
                           Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The masculine understanding of <ref target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland"
                  >Queen Elizabeth</ref> was so captivated by the comic scenes of the historical
               play, in two parts, of <title><ref target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">Henry
                     the Fourth</ref></title>, that she commanded <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> to introduce <ref
                  target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref> in one drama more, and to make him in
                  love.<note>Critics are divided in their support of the theory that <ref
                     target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland">Queen Elizabeth</ref> ordered the
                  creation of <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Merry Wives of
                     Windsor</title></hi>.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland">Her Majesty</ref> had more respect
               for <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref> than for the tender passion, or
               she certainly would not have wished it disgraced by such a votary. But possibly there
               might be morality in her design; for volumes, written against the fatal delusions of
               love, could never be so effectual a cure to sighing youth, or pining damsel, as to
               behold their own disorder raging in the bosom of one so little formed to excite a
               sympathetic sensation. </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> protected love from so
               vile an habitation, and placed avarice in its stead.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref>, speaking of this expedient of
               the great poet in favour of love, has bestowed the highest possible encomium on that
               prevailing power, by declaring, <quote>That by any real passion of tenderness, the
                  selfish craft, the careless jollity, and the easy luxury of <ref
                     target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref>, must have suffered so much
                  abatement, that little of his former cast could have remained. <ref
                     target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref> could not love, but by ceasing to
                  be <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref>.<note>From <ref
                        target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> and <ref
                        target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' <hi rendition="#italics"
                           ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                              Shakspeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                           Commentators</title></hi> (1773), vol. 1, pp. 311-312.</note></quote></p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
            <pb n="4"/>

            <p>Thus is love proclaimed as a general purifier from evil by one of our strictest
               moralists. The passion must therefore be ever considered as counterfeit, when
               unaccompanied by virtue and honour.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> allows this play to be "exactly
                  formed;"<note>From <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Essay Of Dramatick Poesy</title></hi> (1668), p.
                  47.</note> whilst the former critic says, "The conduct of this drama is deficient;
               the action begins and ends often before the conclusion, and the different parts might
               change place without inconvenience."<note><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel"
                     >Johnson</ref>'s comment in his and <ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge"
                     >Steevens</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>, With
                        the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators</title></hi>
                  (1773), vol. 1, p. 312.</note> He, nevertheless, acknowledges the work to be a
               fine combination of dramatic circumstances, and shelters the author's failings under
               the royal command. To write at command is indeed of all labour the most severe, as
               far as the torments of the mind, in general, exceed those of the body.</p>

            <p>Though it is said, that the <ref target="people.html#ElizabethIQueenofEngland"
                  >Queen</ref> was graciously pleased to express her approbation of "<title>The
                  Merry Wives</title>," when she attended the representation, yet the author was not
               so easily satisfied as his royal auditor; and after the date of its first
               performance, he added various alterations and improvements.</p>

            <p>Independent of its merit as a comedy, the production is curious to the highest
               degree, as a faithful reporter of the manners and usages of that age, which the
               unadorned dialogue, and the unaffected personages of the drama, would confirm, even
               if <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>'s name was not
               affixed to the work.</p>

            <p>This is one among the number of his dramas, that can never be performed but when the
               theatre in which it is played has in its service an actor of very high and very
               peculiar abilities. <ref target="people.html#HendersonJohn">Henderson</ref>, about
               twenty <pb n="5"/>years ago, answered this description, and his <ref
                  target="people.html#Falstaff">Sir John Falstaff</ref> was accounted his very best
               character. Not, indeed, the individual <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Sir
                  John</ref> of this comedy, which is far inferior, both in wit and humour, to the
               same man in <title><ref target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">Henry the
                     Fourth</ref></title>.</p>

            <p>From the time of <ref target="people.html#HendersonJohn">Henderson</ref>'s death,
               attempts had been made to revive <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Sir John</ref>,
               but he was cold as his great representative, till <ref
                  target="people.html#KembleStephen">Mr. Stephen Kemble</ref> was engaged to
               personate him a few nights at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>,
               and brought him to life for the period of his engagement. Since when, <ref
                  target="people.html#CookeGeorge">Cooke</ref>, at <ref
                  target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, undertook his
               resuscitation, and will make him live as long as he lives himself. </p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
